expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1944</fr:anchor><fr:addr>hodge-theory-iii-0.4</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-0.4.xml</fr:route><fr:number>III.0.4</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-terminology-and-notation</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
    A <fr:em>mixed Hodge <fr:tex>A</fr:tex>-structure</fr:em> consists of an <fr:tex>A</fr:tex>-module <fr:tex>H_A</fr:tex> of finite type, a finite increasing filtration <fr:tex>W</fr:tex> on the <fr:tex>A\otimes \mathbb {Q}</fr:tex>-vector space <fr:tex>H_{A\otimes \mathbb {Q}}=H_A\otimes \mathbb {Q}</fr:tex>, and a finite decreasing filtration <fr:tex>F</fr:tex> on the <fr:tex>\mathbb {C}</fr:tex>-vector space <fr:tex>H_\mathbb {C}=H_A\otimes _A\mathbb {C}</fr:tex>.
    We demand that the <fr:tex>(\operatorname {Gr}_n^W(H_{A\otimes \mathbb {Q}}),\operatorname {Gr}_n^W(F))</fr:tex> be Hodge <fr:tex>A\otimes \mathbb {Q}</fr:tex>-structures.
    For <fr:tex>A=\mathbb {Z}</fr:tex> (resp. <fr:tex>A=\mathbb {Q}</fr:tex>), we recover <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-2.3.1"
href="hodge-theory-ii-2.3.1.xml"
taxon="Definition"
number="2.3.1"></fr:ref> (resp. <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-2.3.8"
href="hodge-theory-ii-2.3.8.xml"
number="2.3.8"></fr:ref>);
    the results of <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-2.3"
href="hodge-theory-ii-2.3.xml"
number="2.3"></fr:ref> carry over as they are.
  </fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1945</fr:anchor><fr:addr>hodge-theory-iii-0.5</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-0.5.xml</fr:route><fr:number>III.0.5</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-terminology-and-notation</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
    Let <fr:tex>\mathscr {E}</fr:tex> be a subset of <fr:tex>\mathbb {Z}\times \mathbb {Z}</fr:tex>.
    We say that a mixed Hodge structure <fr:tex>H</fr:tex> is of <fr:em>degree <fr:tex>\mathscr {E}</fr:tex></fr:em> if the Hodge numbers <fr:tex>h^{pq}</fr:tex> are zero for <fr:tex>(p,q)\not \in \mathscr {E}</fr:tex>.
  </fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1946</fr:anchor><fr:addr>hodge-theory-iii-0.6</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-0.6.xml</fr:route><fr:number>III.0.6</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-terminology-and-notation</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
    From now on, we denote by <fr:tex>\Omega _X^\bullet (\log  D)</fr:tex> what we previously denoted by <fr:tex>\Omega _X^\bullet \langle  D\rangle </fr:tex> (<fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-3.1.2"
href="hodge-theory-ii-3.1.2.xml"
number="3.1.2"></fr:ref>).
  </fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1947</fr:anchor><fr:addr>hodge-theory-iii-0.7</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-0.7.xml</fr:route><fr:number>III.0.7</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-terminology-and-notation</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
    Unless explicitly stated otherwise, <fr:em>scheme</fr:em> means "scheme of finite type over <fr:tex>\mathbb {C}</fr:tex>", and a <fr:em>sheaf</fr:em> on a scheme <fr:tex>X</fr:tex> is a sheaf on the underlying topological space of <fr:tex>X_\mathrm {an}</fr:tex>.
  </fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:context><fr:related></fr:related><fr:backlinks><fr:tree
