root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1952</fr:anchor><fr:addr>hodge-theory-iii-8.1.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-8.1.1.xml</fr:route><fr:number>8.1.1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.1</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
    Let <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> be as in <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-iii-0.3"
href="hodge-theory-iii-0.3.xml"
number="III.0.3"></fr:ref>.
    Then a <fr:em>Hodge <fr:tex>A</fr:tex>-complex</fr:em> <fr:tex>K</fr:tex> of weight <fr:tex>n</fr:tex> consists of

    
 <html:ol
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(𝛼) &quot;">
        a complex <fr:tex>K_A\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathrm {D}^+(A)</fr:tex> such that <fr:tex>\operatorname {H}^k(K_A)</fr:tex> is an <fr:tex>A</fr:tex>-module of finite type for all <fr:tex>k</fr:tex>;
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(𝛽) &quot;">
        a filtration <fr:tex>F</fr:tex> on <fr:tex>K_A\otimes \mathbb {C}</fr:tex>, i.e. a filtered complex <fr:tex>(K_\mathbb {C},F)\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathrm {D}^+F(\mathbb {C})</fr:tex>, and an isomorphism <fr:tex>\alpha \colon  K_\mathbb {C}\simeq  K_A\otimes \mathbb {C}</fr:tex> in <fr:tex>\mathrm {D}^+(\mathbb {C})</fr:tex>.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p><fr:p>
    The following axioms have to be satisfied:

    <fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1267</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Axiom</fr:taxon><fr:addr>hodge-theory-iii-8.1-ch1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-8.1-ch1.xml</fr:route><fr:number>CH1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.1.1</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
        The differential <fr:tex>d</fr:tex> of <fr:tex>K_\mathbb {C}</fr:tex> is strictly compatible with the filtration <fr:tex>F</fr:tex>;
        in other words, the spectral sequence defined by <fr:tex>(K_\mathbb {C},F)</fr:tex> degenerates at <fr:tex>E_1</fr:tex> (i.e. <fr:tex>E_1=E_\infty </fr:tex>) <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.2"
href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.2.xml"
taxon="Proposition"
number="1.3.2"></fr:ref>.
      </fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>

    <fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1268</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Axiom</fr:taxon><fr:addr>hodge-theory-iii-8.1-ch2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-8.1-ch2.xml</fr:route><fr:number>CH2</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.1.1</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
        For all <fr:tex>k</fr:tex>, the filtration <fr:tex>F</fr:tex> on <fr:tex>\operatorname {H}^k(K_\mathbb {C})\simeq \operatorname {H}^k(K_A)\otimes \mathbb {C}</fr:tex> defines a Hodge <fr:tex>A</fr:tex>-structure of weight <fr:tex>n+k</fr:tex> on <fr:tex>\operatorname {H}^k(K_A)</fr:tex>, i.e. the filtration <fr:tex>F</fr:tex> is <fr:tex>(n+k)</fr:tex>-opposite to its complex conjugate (which makes sense, since <fr:tex>A\subset \mathbb {R}</fr:tex>).
      </fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:backlinks><fr:references></fr:references></fr:backmatter></fr:tree>